comment.undefined: This class describes the three cantiche into which the Divina Coomedia is divided: Inferno, Purgatorio, Paradiso.
This class allows you to describe people and characters (both real and fictional) related to Divina Commedia.
This class describes some of the modern editors of Divina Commedia.
This class describes all the real places mentioned in the Divina Commedia.
This class describes all the literary works related to Divina Commedia.
This class describes the souls of people who are in heaven.
This class describes the souls of people who are in the hell.
This class describe the style to which a literary work belongs.
This class describes the references related to Divina Commedia.
This class describes the editions of the Divina Commedia.
This class describes all the people related to Divina Commedia that really existed.
This class describes the souls of people who are in Purgatorio.
This class allows you to describe the demons of the hell.
This class describes the commentary apparatus, divided by lines, of the editions of the Divina Commedia.
This class describes the lines of each canto of the Divina Commedia.
This class describes all the souls related to Divina Commedia. It includes the souls of the "Paradiso", "Purgatorio" and "Inferno".
This class describes all the canti in which a cantica is composed.
This class describes all the places, both fictional and real, related to Divina Commedia.
This class describes all the fictional places mentioned by Dante in the Divina Commedia.
This class allows you to describe the angels of the heaven.
This class describes the fictional characters related to DIvina Commedia. In particular, it includes angels, demons and the souls of the people.
This class describes all the literary elements that we took in consideration to analyze a Canto of the Divina Commedia.

This data property allows you to link an agent to the name by which he/she is named in the Divina Commedia. In particular we refer only to the proper name and not to the periphrasis that individuates a character.
This data property allows you to link an agent to the name by which he/she is most widely known.
This object property allows you to describe the relations between the people that have inspired the creation of the souls and the souls themselves.
This data property allows you to link a literary element to its title.
This data property allows you to link a literary element to its textual content.
This data property allows you to link an agent to its viaf and/or dbpedia identifier.
This data property allows you to express the number of canti of a cantica.
This data property allows you to express the year (or range of years) in which a literary work has been written.
This object property allows you to link a literary work to its style.
This object property allows you to describe the classification of the souls that are in the Inferno, Purgatorio and Paradiso.
This object property allows you to link a Canto to its lines.
This object property allows you to link a line to other related literary works and  lines of other Canti  of the Divina Commendia,
This object property allows you to link a line to its commentary apparatus.
This object property allows you to link a litarary work to its author.
This object property allows you to link a line to the places it refers to.
This object property allows you to link the major structure  with its subparts.
This object property allows you to link the commentary to its edition.
This data property allows you to express the number of lines of a canto.
This property allows you to connect people's souls with the characters they are inspired by.
This object property allows you to link a line to the characters it refers to.
This object property allows you to link the Divina Commedia to its editions.
